                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">
                                        <placeName>Louisville Ky</placeName>
                                        <date>January 15th 1852</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">
                                        <addressee>Revd Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                                        <placeName>Ph<hi rend="sup">a</hi></placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Respected and Dear Sir,</p>
                              <p>I hope that you are home by this time and that your trip
                                                  <sic>trough</sic> the states<lb/> will have had
                                        the effect of improving your health and of
                                                  <sic>strenghtening</sic> and<lb/> renewing your
                                        energies to future spiritual labor.</p>
                              <p>I am in possession of your kind letter dated <placeName>St.
                                                  Louis</placeName>
                                        <date>Dec. 18th</date> but fearing the<lb/> answer would not
                                        reach you in time, as there <sic>were</sic> no mail-boats
                                                  <del>g</del> running,<lb/> I thought it advisable
                                        to omit it.</p>
                              <p>With this letter I mail one to the Asmonean containing a statement
                                        of<lb/> the proceedings taken in your behalf, while in this
                                        city. I will give you<lb/> on the other side the substance
                                        of my correspondence, which would have<lb/> reached
                                                  <placeName>New York</placeName> long before this,
                                        were it not for an approval it had<lb/> to undergo at our
                                        Board of Trustees.</p>
                              <p>I am inclined to believe that all your subscribers would like to
                                        receive<lb/> the Occident for <date>January</date>, as they,
                                        or the most of them, are <del>desirou</del><lb/> desirous to
                                        know something of your doings in other places also. I<lb/>
                                        would therefore humbly advise you to begin with the next
                                        number,<lb/> if you deem it expedient and till<add>?</add>
                                        up to spirit charge your abane<add>?</add>.</p>
                              <p>Please let me hear from you, as soon you are arrived in
                                                  <placeName>Ph<hi rend="sup"
                                        >a</hi></placeName><lb/> my wife requested me to give you
                                        her best respects.<lb/>
                                        <persName>Straus</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Lirhten<add>?</add></persName>,
                                                  <persName>Lowensohn</persName>,
                                                  <persName>Oberudarfer</persName> and all your
                                        friends—and<lb/> there are a good many—return their
                                        heartfelt regard and esteem<lb/> to you.</p>
                              <p>May the Lord grant you many years of uninterrupted health and
                                        happi<lb/>ness, to enable you to reap the fruits of your
                                        sowing.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(8)">Your devoted friend and obedient servant</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">
                                        <persName role="author">BHGotthelf</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">for the Occident, by request of the
                                        Congregation Adath <sic>Isral</sic><lb/>
                                        <placeName>Louisville</placeName></p>
                              <p rend="align(center)">Presentation of a Silver Goblet</p>
                              <p rend="align(center)">to</p>
                              <p rend="align(center)">
                                        <persName>Revd Isaac Leeser</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p/>
                              <p><placeName>Louisville Ky.</placeName>
                                        <persName>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Isaac Leeser</persName>
                                        visited this city. He arrived here on the morning<lb/> of
                                        the <date>11th of December</date> and as soon as this fact
                                        became known, a meeting<lb/> of the Board was convened by
                                        order of our respected President, <persName>M. Straus<lb/>
                                                  Esqr.</persName>, in consequence of which the
                                                  <persName>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Is.
                                                  Leeser</persName> received a form at
                                        invitation<lb/> to lecture on <date>Sabbath</date> morning
                                        following. The Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Gentleman kindly
                                        assen<lb/>ted and delighted his numerous audience in a very
                                        able and luminous<lb/> discourse.—On <date>Sunday</date>
                                        afternoon a general meeting was called<lb/> and after
                                        stating the object of the meeting the following
                                        Resolutions<lb/> were unanimously adopted:</p>
                              <p><hi rend="underline">Resolved</hi>, that as small token of the
                                        appreciation in which the <persName>Rev<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >d</hi><lb/> Isaac Leeser</persName> is held by
                                        this Congregation, he be presented with a Silver<lb/> Goblet
                                        bearing a suitable inscription.</p>
                              <p><hi rend="underline">Resolved</hi>, that the presentation shall
                                        take place on <date>Monday evening,<lb/> the 8<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >th</hi> of Dec.</date> in the presence of the
                                        whole Congregation, and that the<lb/> Rev<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >d</hi> Gentleman be invited to attend.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">In accordance with these Resolutions the members
                                        of the Congre<lb/>gation repaired on <date>Monday</date>
                                        evening to the Kofsath<add>?</add> Hotel, the ap<lb/>pointed
                                        place of meeting. <persName>Mr. M. Straus</persName>
                                        presided and, as usual,<lb/> after stating the object of the
                                        convocation selected a committee<lb/> of five to draft
                                        Resolutions suitable for the occasion—and<lb/> the following
                                        Resolutions were proposed, seconded and unanimously<lb/>
                                        carried: (there follow the Resolutions, a copy of which were
                                        handed to you.)</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Signed, <persName role="author">B. H.
                                                  Gotthelf</persName>, <persName>Z. A.
                                                  Jefsel</persName>, <persName>B. Sachs</persName>,
                                                  <persName>L. Silberman</persName>, <persName>H.
                                                  Stern</persName>}Committee<lb/> After the
                                        unanimous adoption of the foregoing Resolutions, a
                                        Committee<lb/> was appointed to request the <persName>Rev<hi
                                                  rend="sup">d</hi> I. L.</persName> to join the
                                        meeting. When<lb/> he made his appearance, these Resolutions
                                        were read to him by the</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p><persName>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> B H. Gotthelf</persName>, the
                                        Chairman of the Committee, after which <persName>M. Straus
                                                  Esqr</persName><lb/> by presenting the Goblet
                                        spoke very feelingly in substance as fellows:—</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">„Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Sir, It affords me great
                                        and infinite pleasure to have been se<lb/> „lected as the
                                        organ of the religious body over which I have the honor<lb/>
                                        „to preside, to request your acceptance of this goblet,
                                        which I hold in<lb/> „my hand—and in doing so, I must ask
                                        your kind indulgence if<lb/> „you find, that I am not able
                                        to do justice to so interesting a<lb/> „subject, not being
                                        accustomed to public speaking.</p>
                              <p>„  This Silver Cup is not given to you to value the precious
                                        metal<lb/> „it contains, nor is it given as a renumeration
                                        for the very efficient<lb/> „and able services you so
                                        voluntarily rendered us on <date>Sabbath</date>
                                        morning,<lb/> „but Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Sir, it is
                                        presented to you as a small token of the high<lb/> „respect
                                        we entertain towards one, whose best years have been
                                        spent<lb/> „in the unswerving, unwavering and unflinching
                                        duty of defending the<lb/> „rights and privileges of our
                                        coreligionists; whose daily task has been to<lb/> „spread
                                        abroad and at home a true knowledge of our Holy Faith
                                        and<lb/> „of the duties incumbent on us as a nation to which
                                        such glorious<lb/> „promises are held out.</p>
                              <p>„  When we reflect, Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Sir, on all that you
                                        have done so maintain<lb/> „the true dignity of
                                                  <placeName>Israel</placeName>, so implant in our
                                        youth the „fear of the Lord<lb/> „the beginning of wisdom",
                                        to <sic>instil</sic> among our fellow-citizens a current
                                        appre<lb/>„ciation of the Jewish character—, the numerous
                                        works that have ema<lb/>„nated from your pen—: we cannot but
                                        admire the versatility of your<lb/> „talents, and to hail
                                        with sentiments of profound pleasure the opportunity<lb/>
                                        „you have so kindly afforded us of becoming acquainted
                                        personally with<lb/> „one, whose well-earned fame is widely
                                        spread over the four corners of<lb/> „the globe; and I speak
                                        but the united sentiments of this congregation, when<lb/> „I
                                        assure you, that we will al<del>l</del>ways look up to you
                                        as our guide, as our teacher.</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>„  May He, in whose Holy service you so faithfully ministered and
                                        for<lb/> „whose Glory you still labor, retain you ever in
                                        His Holy Keeping; may<lb/> „He <sic>strenghten</sic> you to
                                        complete your task; may Health, Long Life<lb/> „and
                                        Prosperity be long accorded you; and may a <add>?</add>
                                        of<lb/> „Glory await you in the realms above"!—</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">The inscription was then read: „Presented by the
                                        Congregation<lb/> „Adath Israel <placeName>Louisville
                                                  Ky</placeName>, to the <persName>Rev<hi rend="sup"
                                                  >d</hi> Isaac Leeser</persName>, the Champion
                                        of<lb/> „Jewish Rights—<date>Dec. 8th 1851—5612</date>.</p>
                              <p>after which the Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi> Gentleman feelingly
                                        replied in a harangue which<lb/> much affected his attentive
                                        and numerous auditors.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">
                                        <persName role="author">B H. G.</persName>
                              </p>
                              <p>P.S. Dear Sir, you are permitted, to alter, <sic>ammend</sic>,
                                        abridge <add>?</add><lb/> according to your
                                                  <sic>judgement</sic>.-</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">yours</p>
                              <p rend="indent(11)">
                                        <persName role="author">BHG</persName>
                              </p>
